5. Technical Assessment — Data Collection Methods
Four data collection approaches were tested during this research project. The following is an honest assessment of each method.

5.1 Web Search — Highly Effective
Status: ✓ Effective
•	Used to triangulate expert credibility and verify claims made in LinkedIn posts and conference talks.
•	Returned real 2025–26 content from newsletters, Substack articles, and indexed LinkedIn posts.
•	Best use: finding original research, locating conference talk summaries, verifying follower counts and affiliations.

5.2 Web Fetch — Partially Effective
Status: ~ Partial
•	Fetched actual LinkedIn post content, Substack articles, and conference talk transcripts where publicly indexed.
•	Not all LinkedIn content is indexed. Some posts require being logged in to view.
•	Substack articles (Lily Ray, Brendan Hufford) were accessible and fetchable.

5.3 YouTube Transcripts via Supadata API — Feasible
Status: ~ Feasible, not executed in sandbox
•	Supadata API exists and is production-ready. Free tier: 100 requests/month.
•	YouTube.com direct fetch returned 429 (rate-limited / blocked).
•	Supadata requires API key signup — feasible in a live environment, not inside a sandboxed demo.
•	Recommended for collecting Aleyda Solis (Crawling Mondays) and Nathan Gotch YouTube transcripts.

5.4 LinkedIn Scraping — Limited
Status: ~ Limited
•	LinkedIn blocks unauthenticated scraping directly.
•	Post snippets surfaced via Google indexing — adequate for sampling recent themes, not full post text.
•	Manual collection is the reliable path for full post text.
•	Recommended approach: log in, copy post text manually into /research/linkedin-posts/ per author.

Method	Status	Notes
Web search	✓ Effective	Credibility verification, content discovery, 2025–26 material. Best first-pass method.
Web fetch	~ Partial	Works for Substack and indexed posts. LinkedIn requires authentication for full text.
YouTube / Supadata API	~ Feasible	Production-ready. Requires API key. 100 free req/month. Not usable in sandbox.
